head.title: The Clanranald History: The pre-history of Clan Donald

note.p: There is an acute mark indicating the presence of an í but the character itself is difficut to discern. It seem likely that either the right hand descender of the m functions both as part of the letter m and as the letter í, or that the i when written became cobined with the left side of the descender of the n

head.title: The Clanranald History: Gille-Brighde and Somerled
The Clanranald History: The Lordship of the Isles

note.p: The 'a' in the middle of this word is a large letter 'a'.
As Robert is also known as the "lame king" could this be "fe[a]r [a]n ghior[r]a (from girra, http://www.dil.ie/25894)?

Black (0120195) notes this headword but is unsure of the meaning, saying that the "text is perhaps doubtful [and the] meaning certanly is". He postulates a meaning of "in retreat". The present editor, however, understands it to be a form of the Early Gaelic secnap.
The lenition dot is over the Tironian Nota but cannot be part of 'agus'. It has thus been taken to be intended as a lenition marker for the min this word.
Black (0091023) gives this as "ionad" but the present editor is of the opinion that a form of "ingnad" or "engnam" fits the context better with the form here being closer to "ingnad".

head.title: The Clanranald History: Linn nan Creach
The Clanranald History: The early history of Clanranald
Verse on the death of Ailin mac Ruaighri
The Clanranald History: The early history of Clanranald (continued)
Elegy on Allan and his son Ranald

note.p: Black (0090618) takes this as grìobh, 'griffin, claw, talon, warrior, hero, chieftan' but the present editor postulates that it is a Gaelicised version of the English word grief.
EPT, WGI: As this stands for Cú Chulainn I have marked it as a name. Do ye agree? If so, should the name element include just 'cú' or also the definite article?
Black (0002257) took this to be the dative singular of clíathach whereas it is understood to be the dative plural of clíat in the present edition.

head.title: The Clanranald History: The early history of Clanranald (continued)
Elegy for Donald son of Allan

note.p: The present editor posits that this could be a form of the English insect, (https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/96686), with the final couplet potentially meaning "like he was an inect [escaping from] a bird, dancing away from him"
